content.html:
“So, if both numbers have the same number of places, we must look at the actual digits. Is that right?” Jaime asked.

“Yes! We start from the largest place value. If the digits are different, the number with the higher digit is the larger one. Since the price of pizza (23) has a 2 in the tens place and the price of fried chicken (19) has a 1 in the tens place, the price of pizza is higher,” Nic explained. "So, 23 > 19."

“But what about the ones digits? Isn't 3 smaller than 9?” asked Jaime.

“We always start with the largest place values," Nic answered. "In this case, tens are bigger than ones, so we compare the tens-place digits first. If those are equal, then we move on to the second largest ones, and so on, until we come to a place value where the digits are different.”

content.html:
Now, Jaime knows the value of each place, and how the values of the digits can be combined to make a number! He can figure out how much his score is worth. Now he can read his score and compare it with other scores.

Also, Jaime made sure to remember how to compare numbers, so that he could use this skill in the future. Here are his notes. You might want to write them down so that you remember, too:

  • Each place has a different value depending on its location. Each place value is 10 times as big as the next one.

  • We write '>' to mean 'is greater than', and '<' to mean 'is less than'. For example, 23 > 19 and 2 < 3.

  • A number is bigger if it has more place values. If both numbers have the same number of place values, we compare the digits from left to right. The first time we see two different digits, we can say that the number with the bigger digit is the bigger number. For example: 219583 > 219458 because the first three digits from the left are the same for both numbers, and 5 is more than 4 for the fourth digit from the left.

hi.html:
Ab, Jay ko har ek sthaan ka mooly pata hai, aur sankhya banaane ke lie ankon ke moolyon ko kaise jodna hai! Woh yeh pata laga sakta hai ki uska score ka moolya kitna hai. Ab woh apne score ko padh sakata hai dusre score ke saath tulna bhi kar sakata hai.

Jay ne yah yaad rakhe ke liye kuch cheesein likh li. Aap unhen likh sakte ho taaki aapko bhi yaad rahen:

  • Har ek sthaan ka alag mooly hota hai. Har sthaan ka mooly agale vaale se 10 guna bada hai.
  • ham likhte hain > ka matalab se bada hai, aur < ka matalab se kam hai. udaaharan ke lie, 23 > 19 aur 2 < 3.
  • Agar sankhya mein adhik sthaan maan hain, to yeh sankhya badee hai. Agar donon sankhyon mein sthaan maan samaan hain, to ham ankon ki tulana baen se daen tak karte hain. Pehli baar jab ham do sankhyon mein wohi staan pe alag-alag ank dekhte hain, to ham keh sakate hain ki badee ank ke saath wala sankhya badi hai. Udaaharan ke lie: 219583> 219458 kyonki baeen or se pahale teen ank donon sankhyaon ke lie samaan hain, aur 5>4 baen se chauthe ank ke lie.
